turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail in Iowa included a second oversize black Chevy conversion van, dubbed "Scooby-two," which had blue and white New York license plates and was mechanically identical to the original "Scooby" van. The Secret Service often uses decoy vehicles to confuse and discourage potential attackers. The two Scooby vans arrived at Clinton's campaign stop separately but left together in a seven-car motorcade. One of the Scooby vans made a motorist leave the roadway so it could go through a red light and rejoin the caravan.

A mother of six has made a desperate plea for help after a fire destroyed her rented condo in Georgia, leaving her family without anything. The family has lost everything in the fire, including all of their possessions and their home. The mother, Kalimah Dixon, is currently staying with a friend and has been unable to find a permanent home for her family while being unemployed. She has started a GoFundMe page to raise money and is asking for assistance in finding a permanent home for her family. Statement

An Australian couple who entered into a surrogacy agreement in India were informed that the boy born through the agreement would be left stateless, according to documents obtained by the ABC. The couple reportedly wanted a baby girl to "complete their family" and told consular staff they would be leaving the boy behind because they could not afford to raise both children. India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens, and the couple was told that if they returned to Australia without the boy, he would be left stateless. Concerns were also raised that the boy may have been sold. Chief Justice of the Family Court, Diana Bryant, said consular staff had expressed concerns to her that money had changed hands in the arrangement, which could indicate trafficking. If money was paid, any adoption would be deemed invalid under India's Hindu Adoption Act. This case is similar to the recent Baby Gammy case, in which an Australian couple only brought back the girl's twin sister from Thailand. The full story will be aired on ABC's Foreign Correspondent on Tuesday. P

Kecil the one-year-old orangutan, who had a tough start to life after being rejected by his natural mother and a surrogate mother, has found love with second surrogate mother Maggie at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie has raised Kecil for the past 10 months, and the two now have an inseparable bond. Maggie, who has already raised four children and a fifth surrogate, has proved herself as a parent once again. Kecil will go on display for the first time this weekend in two-hour slots between 10am and midday. The pair will eventually become part of an exhibit featuring the zoo's four other orangutans, but at the moment they are living in isolation as would be the case in the wild.

Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet. Pastore believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him, but he thanked Cantona for his praise and acknowledged that he likes good football and goals. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's win against Nice on Saturday and they face Barcelona in the second leg of their Champions League tie on Tuesday, needing to overhaul a 3-1 deficit to progress to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife at Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, has successfully challenged the longstanding practice of clamping and cutting the umbilical cord within seconds of delivery, which has been standard procedure since the 1950s. Burleigh believed that this practice was unnatural and lacked evidence to support it. With the help of other medical professionals, including obstetrician Dr David Hutchon, they amassed evidence suggesting that immediate cord-clamping could harm the baby by depriving it of blood, raising the risk of iron deficiency anaemia, and causing more severe brain damage in premature babies. NICE has now changed its guidelines to recommend that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby. This change allows mothers to have more time with their babies while they are still attached by the cord, and could lead to better health outcomes for children. Despite initial resistance from colleagues, Burleigh persisted in challenging this practice in order to improve maternal and infant health.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. An investigation has been launched into the allegations, which involve abuse of children as young as nine at a displaced persons center near Bangui airport between December 2013 and June 2014. The French defense ministry has denied covering up the scandal and launched an immediate probe into the case when it received a leaked UN report on the subject in July last year. Paula Donovan, co-director of advocacy group AIDS-Free World, saw the report and stated that the children were "hungry and thought they could get some food from the soldiers." A UN employee accused of leaking the report, Anders Kompass, has been suspended, and an unnamed staff member was also suspended for leaking the report. Violence in the Central African Republic has pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels led by former leader Francois Bozize. T

A Texas pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, was arrested for trying to resurrect a two-year-old dead boy at a church in Balch Springs. A video captured Meza using oils and praying for hours while trying to bring the boy back to life during a ceremony. Meza and her husband, Pastor Daniel Meza, who presided over the church services held at their home, were both taken into custody. They have been charged with injury to a child by omission, and Meza is being held on a $100,000 bond. The investigation is ongoing, and more information will be released on Tuesday.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, performed well in the first round of the Betfred World Championship. Higgins, a four-time champion, won his match against Robert Milkins with a score of 10-5, while Dott, a former Crucible champion, won his match against Ricky Walden with a score of 10-8. Higgins is hoping to win his fifth world title and is looking to catch up with players like Ronnie O'Sullivan, who has won more titles and made more century breaks. Dott is aiming to win his second world title, having won it in 2006, and is hopeful about his chances.

Barcelona's Neymar, Dani Alves and Adriano celebrated their victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga with a matching denim outfit, which sparked some criticism. Despite their questionable fashion choice, the trio played an important role in helping the Catalonian side return to the top of the league with a 1-0 win. Neymar and Dani Alves, who are both linked with moves away from the club, posted pictures of the three of them together on Instagram, with the hashtag "vamo to top." Game winner Jeremy Mathieu admitted that his side was poor throughout the match, but they still managed to take the three points thanks to his goal in the 73rd minute. Mathieu praised his defensive partner Gerard Pique for his impressive display against a tough opponent.

Jose Mourinho is planning a bid for Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke and may offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as a makeweight in a part-exchange deal, according to Spanish newspaper AS. The newspaper reports that Mourinho watched Koke, 23, during Atletico's match against Deportivo on Saturday, and although Koke's release clause is around £50million, Chelsea may be willing to pay to add to their midfield, which has looked tired at times this season. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, was instrumental in the club's run to the Champions League final last season, where they lost to Real Madrid. This

Tom Ballard, the son of Alison Hargreaves who died climbing K2 in 1995, plans to climb the same mountain 20 years later. He plans to solo climb the six great north faces of the Alps in winter before attempting K2. Alison Hargreaves was the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen and her decision to climb while raising a young family was controversial but she said fathers who climbed did not face the same criticism. Tom Ballard has clear memories of climbing as a child and has dedicated his life to climbing since having an epiphany at primary school. T

A consortium of companies has claimed to have discovered up to 100 billion barrels of oil worth trillions of pounds in the Weald Basin, an area of England spanning Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire and Kent. UK Oil & Gas Investments has discovered the oil reserves near Gatwick airport and believes it could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. Industry experts remain sceptical and caution that only a fraction of the Weald Basin oil may be accessible for extraction. The exploration site covers just 55 square miles out of 1,100, and the consortium is confident the entire region is oil-rich. However, it is not yet known how much of the area's oil will be easily recoverable, and only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction.

The British Veterinary Association has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls and instead recommended trapping the badgers in cages and then shooting them. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA's ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’. The Environment Secretary has promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election, despite criticism from wildlife groups.

It is stated that modern technology often creates more problems in relationships than benefits, such as social media profiles and smartphones. People can be tempted to check their phones during dates, snap pictures of their food, and constantly update their relationship status. Tips are provided to avoid embarrassing situations, such as keeping phones off the table, not updating Facebook immediately, and avoiding bragging about dates or recording with Google Glass. Page

Tottenham Hotspur are missing Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris for their home match against Aston Villa, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt. On the other hand, Aston Villa will be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood and Scott Sinclair due to injuries, and Carles Gil due to illness. Christian Benteke has been in fine form for Villa, scoring seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances. The match will be held on Saturday at 3pm and the referee is Lee Probert. The odds are Tottenham 4/7, Draw 14/5, and Aston Villa 5/1.

A mother in Australia made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at just 20 weeks after scans showed she had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. After deciding to deliver the baby, the mother contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that transforms donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who have passed away. With the help of Angel Gowns, the mother redesigned her wedding dress into a beautiful outfit for her baby girl to be buried in. The family spent time with the baby, Annabelle, before she passed away and took pictures with her in her dress. Angel Gowns created a replica of the dress for the family to keep in their home and the mother still looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns currently donates outfits to more than 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and deals directly with families and children's charities. To donate or volunteer, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A police constable, Ronnie Lungu, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police. The employment tribunal ruled that the force unlawfully discriminated against the black police constable due to the color of his skin. The 40-year-old was singled out and treated unfairly, with his internal assessments secretly downgraded and derogatory comments made about him based on his color. The force denied the claims but was found to have discriminated against Mr. Lungu. He is still serving as a police constable with the force, but he wants new procedures put in place to tackle discrimination and better education among senior members of staff in how to deal with complaints. The Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police has said they are concerned by the findings and will learn lessons from the case. (

A parent has taught their newborn daughter an unusual skill by filming themselves showing the baby how to suck on a plastic water bottle. The father demonstrates the trick by biting the side of the bottle before prompting the baby to do the same. The video, posted on YouTube, has received over 190,000 views and viewers have described it as "cute" and "adorable". One commenter praised the relationship between the father and daughter, saying "it must feel great to have a daughter like her." Re

A set of rare and valuable photographs has emerged after being put up for auction. The images, taken by photographer Hugh Owen between 1850 and 1855 in Bristol, offer a glimpse into the city's past, more than a century before much of its historic centre was destroyed during the Second World War. The albumen prints, made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives, feature views of the waterfront, city centre, St Mary Redcliffe church, and more. One of the buildings pictured, The Fourteen Stars Tavern, was pulled down in 1857 and has since been replaced by a block of flats. Other buildings have been significantly altered over time, but some areas, such as St John's Gate, have changed little. The images could sell for up to £30,000 at auction tomorrow.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter is trying to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat, who is standing in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary in 2011 and is seeking revenge against Fox's family. Boulter has already given £30,000 to a Ukip candidate in Somerset to defeat Fox and is spending another £30,000 to try to defeat Tugendhat. Boulter said he is seeking revenge for a court case in which a High Court judge awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages. The Tory Party declined to comment.

A six-year-old boy named Charlie Pye from Leamington Spa applied for the job of Aston Villa manager after the sacking of Paul Lambert, and despite missing out on the position, received a letter of encouragement and praise from the current manager, Tim Sherwood. Sherwood wrote that Charlie would have been an ideal candidate for the job, and that the club would like to keep the letter on file "just in case". Charlie has also been appointed captain of his football team, Norton Lindsey, and had suggested appointing his parents as assistant managers. The letter meant a lot to Charlie and he was delighted to receive it.

Atletico Madrid has moved above Valencia in the race for third place in the La Liga standings, following their 2-0 victory over bottom side Cordoba. Atletico's top scorer, Antoine Griezmann, netted the first goal in the fifth minute, while Saul Niguez doubled the lead in the 39th minute. Valencia has 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win against Villarreal, while Real Madrid has 64 points, four behind leaders Barcelona, who play Celta Vigo on Sunday. Europa League champions Sevilla is in fifth place with 58 points, following their 2-0 win over Athletic Bilbao. Cordoba, who is on a 10-match losing streak, is set to equal the worst run in Spain's top flight of 11 defeats suffered by Las Palmas in 1960.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one from Castle Donington, UK, died after taking M-Cat at a house party. Abby Swinfield was partying with friends in Tamworth when she suffered two heart attacks and died of multiple organ failure a week later. Her cousin claims her drink was spiked, while police have arrested a 20-year-old woman on suspicion of supplying drugs. Abby's mother, Kay, is "devastated" over her daughter's death, and her three-year-old son is asking for his mother. The family is "torn apart" by the tragedy.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation which has raised fears for the health of children in the area. Soil underneath a slide at the park showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly double the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. The cause of the radiation is not immediately clear but it is believed to be coming from something buried underneath the park. The playground has been fenced off and the city has set up a health advice office to answer queries from concerned parents.

Amir Khan believes that Kell Brook called him out to get the "one big payday" that has eluded him during his career. Khan thinks that Brook is only interested in the fight for the money and is not a big enough name in the UK to face the world's biggest stars. Khan has announced a fight with Chris Algieri next month but has now backtracked on that, claiming that there are "some more options on the table". Khan will not fight during Ramadan because of his Islamic faith. He insists that he will make a lot of money in the sport regardless of whether he fights Brook, but Brook needs him to make that big money. Khan believes that Brook is not brave enough to fight the top guys like Pacquiao, Mayweather, and Marquez.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunning three-bedroom home, named 'PV14.' The 3,700 square-foot home boasts a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, a 1,400 square-foot roof deck that can fit up to 150 people, and a 360-degree view of White Rock Lake and the city's downtown. The home also features a two-story glass-paneled tower, made out of shipping containers, which reflects the swimming pool. The designers wanted to stay true to the materials that built the home, so all ceilings were left exposed and the shipping container gates were unpainted. The walls of the home are made of sheetrock, and columns had to be placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. The house's open-floor first level, dedicated to entertaining, features polished cement and sleek steel, while the upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors. The home offers deep porches to protect it from direct sunlight while still allowing natural light to seep in. After over two years of design and construction, the couple are preparing to move into their new home.

Jordan Ibe has agreed to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool, keeping him at Anfield until 2020. He has made a notable impact in eight appearances since returning to Liverpool in January, after spending the first half of the season on loan at Derby County. Ibe will sign his new contract this week, and Liverpool are alsoclose to finalising extensions for Jordan Henderson, Martin Skrtel, and young defender Jon Flanagan, whose contract expires in June. The club has also agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year. I

Rik Mayall, a British comedian, died last June and failed to leave a valid will for his £1.2 million estate, which could leave his family with a large inheritance tax bill. The lack of a will could complicate matters for his wife and three adult children, as the estate will be divided according to government intestacy rules, which take into account marital status, children or surviving relatives. Mrs. Mayall was declined to discuss the estate and the apparent lack of a will. The absence of a will may result in a potential tax bill if the amount exceeds the inheritance tax limit of £325,000. The family could avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split the estate and reduce the sum left to the children. The family of Rik Mayall could seek to avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold. The war in Yemen has caused many people to be evacuated from the capital, Sanaa. Countries are working to get their citizens out during a small window when Saudi planes are not bombing the city. Air India is particularly active in this evacuation effort and has evacuated 2,500 people from Yemen. The evacuees are being taken to Djibouti, where they will most likely disperse to their home nations. Many of the evacuees are exhausted and stressed, including Damodar Thakur, a professor who lived in Yemen for 34 years and built a life there. National

An Italian priest has been sacked from a religious order in Taranto after allegations surfaced that he participated in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The priest was dismissed after one of his online lovers contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing evidence of the alleged activities. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios that involved his lover playing the role of Judas Iscariot, who had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The news of the priest's dismissal is the latest sex scandal to engulf the Vatican. The diocese has confirmed the priest's dismissal, but stated that there were no other prelates involved.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among children with older siblings with autism. The study, which analyzed data from about 95,000 young people, found that vaccines had no effect on autism risk, whether or not a sibling in the family was diagnosed with autism. This is consistent with previous studies that have ruled out a link between the MMR vaccine and autism over the past 15 years. Despite concerns over vaccine safety, the study's authors and an accompanying editorial note that the data is clear: there is no relationship between the MMR vaccine and the development of autism in children. A new report by Human Rights Watch has revealed the harrowing accounts of Yazidi women and girls who were kidnapped, beaten, and repeatedly raped by ISIS fighters. The study found that ISIS was taking Yazidi women and children as young as eight as captives, converting them to Islam, and forcing them to marry and have children with their captors. The organization's actions amount to war crimes, the report concludes, and possibly crimes against humanity. Yazidi women and girls who managed to escape their captors require better medical and psychological support after facing traumatic experiences. E

A man named Kenneth Stancil opened fire in the campus library of a North Carolina college on Monday morning, killing one person. Stancil was a former student at Wayne Community College, where he allegedly shot and killed a man working in the school's print shop. Stancil is described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye. A warrant has been issued for his arrest and he is considered extremely dangerous. The college was put on lockdown and SWAT teams raced to the scene. The lockdown was later lifted and students were evacuated building by building. With over

The new chief executive of Rotherham Council could receive a salary up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to the negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council previously offered £160,000 but will now offer up to £200,000 to attract candidates. The rest of the cabinet resigned after a Government report found the council to be "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about exploitation. The council's HR chief suggested that additional incentives may be necessary, but some councillors are uncomfortable with the idea. Das

Cesc Fabregas broke his nose during Chelsea's match against Stoke City and will wear a protective face mask while he recovers. The mask was made by Ortholabsport in Milan and is branded with Fabregas' initials and squad number. Fabregas traveled to Milan on Tuesday with Chelsea's medical director to have the mask fitted. He could return to action as early as Sunday against Queens Park Rangers if selected by manager Jose Mourinho, while John Obi Mikel is expected to return this week. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks with a hamstring injury.

Andros Townsend scored a wonderful goal for England in a 1-1 draw with Italy, silencing critics like Paul Merson who had previously dismissed him. Despite a mixed season for the Tottenham winger, England manager Roy Hodgson continued to show faith in him, which paid off with his impressive goal.

A man has been accused of attempting to murder his cheating wife, who was left with life-threatening injuries after being stabbed eight times by her husband with a kitchen knife. The wife, Amanda, survived the attack and four months later, her husband wrote her a letter from jail requesting her to gather some of his belongings for his trial. Amanda broke down in court as she gave evidence and said she never wanted to hurt her husband, even now. The trial continues.

The UK is planning to open its first three proton beam therapy centres after a cancer-stricken five-year-old boy made a miracle recovery after receiving the treatment. The centres will be available to NHS cancer patients in Cardiff, London and Northumberland by 2017, with the first in Cardiff set to be operational by next year. The announcement comes after the parents of brain cancer sufferer Ashya King told of how he was given the 'all-clear' after receiving proton beam therapy at a centre in Prague. The UK has committed almost £100 million equity finance into the company and a group called Proton Partners International has been formed in the UK following discussions between Professor Sir Chris Evans, the life sciences entrepreneur and UK life sciences and healthcare investors. The centres will provide proton beam therapy, which is a highly-targeted type of radiotherapy that can treat hard-to-reach cancers with a lower risk of damaging the surrounding tissue and causing side effects. Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia because it is cheaper than training them in Britain. The selection process, held at five-star hotels, is quick and easy, and applicants receive an email the next day to find out if they have a job. The NHS has also been recruiting nurses from Spain and Portugal. Many British paramedics are choosing to work as "advanced practitioners" in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centers due to the high demand and stress levels. The Australian paramedics hired by the London Ambulance Service are offered a salary of £30,200, which is lower than the £4,500 "golden hello" payment. The director of operations at London Ambulance Service says that recruiting from Australia is a temporary solution until more paramedics are trained in the UK. The

Chelsea have turned to the latest fitness technology to help them win the Premier League title. The club has partnered with fitness equipment provider Technogym, who have installed state-of-the-art equipment at Chelsea's Cobham training ground. Players including Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured working out, while a video of young defender Kurt Zouma training has been shared on the club's Twitter account. Chelsea assistant first team fitness coach Carlos Lalin has praised the partnership, saying that Technogym is the best in the industry. Technogym's founder and President Nerio Alessandri has also welcomed the collaboration, stating that both Chelsea and Technogym share a strong dedication to performance. Fem

It is reported that 11-month-old babies have mastered the fundamentals of physics, showing surprise when objects such as a ball appear to defy the laws of physics. They also reacted with surprise when puppets demonstrated different social situations like bullying and friendship, and they were more interested in playing with the ball than a new toy in an experiment. The researchers concluded that infants use what they already know about the world to form predictions and when these predictions are shown to be wrong, infants use this as a special opportunity for learning. The study suggests that babies are "remarkably sophisticated thinkers" and are born with certain fundamental knowledge about the world. Rep

Manny Pacquiao, a Filipino boxer, trained on the streets of Los Angeles for his upcoming fight against Floyd Mayweather. He ran along the trail at Griffith Park and was joined by his dog Pacman. Pacquiao demonstrated his impressive footwork by shadow boxing in front of watching spectators. The boxer also worked on his core strength during a training session on the mats. Pacquiao revealed the multicolored mouthguard he will wear during the $300 million Las Vegas showdown. Stat

A cat named Biso has been freed after being stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years. He was rescued thanks to a social media campaign and the efforts of animal rights activists. Biso survived in the station thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who fed him scraps of food every day. Uncle Abdo named the cat and would visit the station to feed him during the Egyptian Revolution in 2011. Staff at the station initially tried to rescue Biso years ago, but he was too scared to come out from behind the wall. Animal activists eventually rescued Biso on March 13 after a picture of his tail was posted on Facebook. Biso quickly ran away after his rescue and Uncle Abdo is still searching for him inside the station.

At least 35 workers have been killed and a dairy factory in Yemen has been set ablaze after it was hit by airstrikes that targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida. The Saudi-led coalition launched the air campaign last week to defeat Shiite rebels in Yemen, and today's airstrikes came as Saudi Arabia hinted that it was prepared to launch a ground invasion in Yemen. The U.N. children's agency, UNICEF, reported that 62 children were killed and 30 wounded during the fighting in Yemen over the past week, with high civilian casualties in the escalating crisis.

A truck collided with a car on an elevated highway in Boston, causing delays for commuters on the subway and rail tracks. Both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. The cause of the collision is still under investigation.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall commended his young players after a narrow defeat in the European Cup and stated that the team will not overspend in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. The club's millionaire chairman had suggested that the salary cap should be lifted to allow them to compete at the highest level in Europe, but McCall clarified that they will only bring in new players if they fit their long-term plan, and not for the sake of signing marquee players.

The bodies of four alleged terrorists who killed 148 people at Garissa University College in Kenya were paraded in a pickup truck through the streets of the town today. One of the survivors, Cynthia Cheroitich, who spent two days hiding in a wardrobe, was rescued and taken to hospital for counseling. Dozens of survivors were found yesterday, including four more who were rescued from the university. bearing

Arsenal must decide soon if they want to sign Petr Cech from Chelsea this summer. Cech is expected to leave Chelsea after losing his starting spot and will hold talks with manager Jose Mourinho to confirm his decision. Cech's valuation could be a major obstacle for Arsenal, who may also face reluctance from Chelsea to sell to a Premier League rival. However, Cech would consider moving to Arsenal and hopes his long service at Chelsea will allow him to make the final decision on his next move. Signing Cech would significantly strengthen Arsenal's team.

Frankie Dettori will not be riding horses for Sheikh Joaan Al Thani in France this summer as the owner has signed Gregory Benoist for that purpose. The recruitment of Benoist is not a snub for Dettori, as it was simply not logistically feasible to have one jockey covering both Britain and France, where Sheikh Joaan has over 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Thierry Jarnet will still ride Treve, the dual Arc winner, and Dettori will continue to ride British horses in France.

Lois Lilienstein, a co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at age 78 from a rare form of cancer. The show ran on Nickelodeon during the early 1990s and was known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein left the trio in 2000 and was born in Chicago in 1936. Sally Catto, general manager, programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to her for her contribution to Canadian kids TV.

French freediving champion Guillaume Néry jumps into the world's second deepest underwater sinkhole, Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, without scuba gear and holds his breath for minutes on end. The footage is filmed by his girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier and shows Néry reaching what appears to be the bottom of the 660ft hole, although he revealed later that it was done for artistic reasons. Free divers use mind-body control techniques to push self-induced apnoea to the limits and can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes. Gar

A suicide bomber from the ISIS Wilayat Khorasan group blew himself up in front of the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, early Saturday morning, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The terrorist group claimed responsibility for the attack and stated that the bomber was targeting government workers collecting their pay at the bank. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack and condemned it. The United Nations denounced the violence and warned that the use of suicide attacks in densely populated areas may amount to a war crime. The attack comes as concerns about ISIS's involvement in the region have been growing this year, including the death of a former Taliban commander who had become a recruiter for ISIS in Afghanistan in a drone strike earlier this year. Laura Wells, a plus-size model, has launched a new swimwear line called "Reef Culture" in collaboration with Swimsuits For All. The entire collection is made from 100% recycled materials and is inspired by the ocean with coral reef scenes featured throughout. The swimsuits are available in sizes 10-24 and include one and two-piece suits with different cuts and styles to cater to all shapes. Wells revealed that the idea for the collaboration came about through a conversation she had with the brand while she was working with them on a photoshoot. The primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping the price point affordable.

TrackYourDose is an iOS app developed by Germany-based esooka that records a user's personal radiation exposure from changes in their location, medical examinations, and flights. It uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists at PTB in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. The app measures cosmic radiation, gamma radiation, and neutron radiation on the ground. It also accounts for ionizing radiation from medical examinations such as X-rays or CT scans. The app calculates radiation exposure during flights, including ten-hour flights across the North Atlantic, which result in radiation exposure between 50 µSv and 100 µSv. Airline pilots are at risk of deadly skin cancer due to cockpit radiation similar to levels from tanning beds. The app helps pilots monitor their radiation exposure and take necessary precautions.

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility after it was linked to a foodborne illness that resulted in the deaths of three people. The company made the decision 'out of an abundance of caution' to ensure the safety of its products and maintain the trust of its consumers. The CDC has recommended that consumers not eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the Oklahoma facility and that retailers and institutions do not sell or serve them. The recall affected ten products that were produced on a production line at the company's headquarters in Texas. The investigation to determine whether the illnesses are related to exposure to Blue Bell products is ongoing. The UK government has pledged to protect the Falkland Islands from "Argentine bullying" after Argentina took legal action against British companies exploring for oil off the islands. Argentina had accused three British and two US companies of working without permission in a basin 120 miles north of the islands, which it considers part of its territory. The UK Foreign Secretary, Philip Hammond, said that President Cristina Kirchner's threats against businesses working with the Falkland Islands were "as hollow as they are illegal", and the islanders could rely on the UK to protect them. The diplomatic row over the fate of the Falklands has worsened in recent weeks following the UK government's announcement to invest £180m in the islands' defences over the next ten years.

Passengers on a Delta Air Lines plane experienced a scare when an odor of smoke was detected shortly after landing at LaGuardia Airport. Firefighters in protective gear surrounded the plane and used a thermal imaging camera to search for a potential heat source. Passengers were kept on board for about 45 minutes while the situation was handled. The Delta Air Lines spokesperson stated that the flight crew noticed a smoky odor in the cockpit while taxiing to the gate, and out of an abundance of caution, the engines were shut down and the airport fire department was notified. The safety of Delta's customers and crew is always a top priority. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance.

David Luiz has been ruled out for at least four weeks after tearing a hamstring during a match against Marseille. In his latest Instagram post, the Brazilian defender is seen sporting a new hairstyle in the form of a man bun. While his teammates find the new look amusing, Luiz's injury is not a laughing matter for manager Laurent Blanc, who will now have to deal with the defender's absence as they seek to defend their Ligue 1 and Champions League titles this season.

US President Barack Obama has stated that diplomacy is the best way to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. He believes that a comprehensive, long-term deal with Iran is the best option and plans to keep Congress apprised of the details of the deal. Obama has highlighted the rigorous inspections that Tehran will be subject to and stated that if Iran cheats, the world will know it. The deal is not based on trust, but on unprecedented verification. The US and six world powers have determined the outlines of a landmark agreement with Iran to curb its nuclear program and potentially lift economic sanctions, but the final deal has yet to be reached. The agreement has been met with skepticism by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and other critics, who say it would legitimize Iran's nuclear program, bolster Iran's economy, and increase Iran's aggression and terror in the Middle East.

A 12-year-old girl with leukemia has been kicked out of school for poor attendance and academic performance, despite the school making accommodations for her illness. Rose McGrath, who has been attending the Battle Creek Catholic Schools her entire life, said school was the one place she felt normal. Her mother said the school's decision to dismiss Rose was "heartbreaking," and that the accommodations made for her were woefully inadequate. Despite being done with cancer treatment, Rose still experiences illness and finds it difficult to attend classes and complete schoolwork. Her parents filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights and are waiting for a response.

Passive smoking has been shown to affect humans and now researchers have found that plants can also take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. This may explain why some food crops and plant-derived products contain high levels of nicotine, even though it is banned in insecticides. Peppermint plants were used in experiments and shown to take up high levels of nicotine from contaminated soils and from cigarette smoke. The study suggests that there may be other sources of nicotine in plants besides the illegal use of insecticides and sheds light on the success of farming practices such as crop rotation and co-cultivation of certain vegetables. The finding is interesting to the food industry and proves that substances such as alkaloids can be transferred from one plant to another.

Despite suffering a 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final, Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. Players can face grim outcomes such as being separated from their families by human traffickers, sold to militia groups, or beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean Sea. A three-legged cat named Freeman was brutally mauled to death by two dogs in a neighbors' front garden. A woman who appears to call over the dogs is seen walking away and leaving the cat to die. The owner of the cat, Tracy Lynch, has expressed her devastation and sadness at the callous lack of action by the dog owners to check on the cat after the attack. The police are investigating the incident.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation for raising her pet pig, named Five Flowers, as a beloved member of her household. The pig weighs 187lbs and she even shares a bed with it. Despite the husband being "tolerant" of the relationship, the dog is reportedly envious of the pig's attention. Ms. Zhu dresses, walks, and even puts a body harness on her pig, and even makes sure it is well-tended by leading a trail of green vegetables from the bedroom to the bathroom for grooming. Ms. Zhu, who works at a publishing company and lives in Beijing with her husband and other pets, has 40,000 followers on Weibo, and the latest pictures of the pig in bed have received over 13,000 retweets and almost 9,000 supportive comments.
